---
import Layout from "@layouts/Layout.astro";
import Container from "@components/Container.astro";
import Link from "@components/Link.astro";
import { ABOUT } from "@consts";
---

<Layout title={ABOUT.TITLE} description={ABOUT.DESCRIPTION}>
  <Container>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div
        class="flex flex-col gap-5 sm:flex-row sm:items-start"
        style="padding-bottom: 1.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);"
      >
        <img
          src="/images/headshot.png"
          alt="Adam M. Rahman"
          class="size-24 shrink-0 rounded-full object-cover"
          style="border: 1px solid var(--rule);"
        />
        <div>
          <h1 class="page-heading-sm">Adam Rahman</h1>
          <p class="body-text-sm" style="margin-top: 0.25rem;">
            Software engineer at IBM &middot; M.S. Computer Engineering, NYU
            Tandon &middot; B.A. Theater & Computer Science, Wesleyan
          </p>
          <p class="body-text-xs" style="margin-top: 0.35rem;">
            Engineer, poet, and theatermaker. My work keeps returning to the
            same questions: who gets seen, who gets counted, and the dignity of
            people who cannot opt out.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="about-layout">
        <article class="prose about-prose">
          <p>
            I'm a software engineer at <Link
              href="https://www.ibm.com/z"
              external>IBM</Link
            > in New York City, working on test automation and technology modernization
            for the IBM Z mainframe platform. I replace legacy mainframe testing tools
            with modern open-source frameworks: porting
            <Link href="https://grafana.com/oss/k6/" external>Grafana k6</Link>
            natively to z/OS, building Locust-based load testing for 3270 terminals,
            and creating CI/CD pipelines that bring current DevOps practice to enterprise
            mainframe infrastructure. Several of those tools are open source, including
            <Link href="/dev/xk6-tn3270">xk6-tn3270</Link>, <Link
              href="/dev/xk6-llm">xk6-llm</Link
            >, and <Link href="/dev/fromjcl">fromjcl</Link>.
          </p>
          <p>
            I hold a B.A. in Theater and Computer Science from <Link
              href="https://www.wesleyan.edu/"
              external>Wesleyan University</Link
            >, where I was a <Link
              href="https://www.wesleyan.edu/patricelli/"
              external>Patricelli Center Fellow</Link
            >, and I'm finishing an M.S. in Computer Engineering at <Link
              href="https://engineering.nyu.edu/"
              external>NYU Tandon</Link
            >. At Wesleyan I also built <Link
              href="https://wesleyanargus.com/2019/04/23/immersive-imaginary-exhibit-brings-augmented-reality-to-mac650/"
              external>SoundStoneVR</Link
            >, a spatial audio VR composition tool shown at the Immersive
            Imaginary exhibition.
          </p>
          <p>
            Outside that work, I build tools at the intersection of geospatial
            AI and humanitarian use. <Link href="/dev/dream-meridian"
              >DreamMeridian</Link
            >
            runs AI geospatial queries entirely offline on a Raspberry Pi, for refugee
            camps and disaster zones with no reliable network. It placed 2nd out of
            more than 1,600 entries in the ARM AI Developer Challenge, and the work
            was <Link
              href="https://engineering.nyu.edu/news/meet-adam-munawar-rahman-leveraging-ai-humanitarian-use"
              external>profiled by NYU Tandon Engineering</Link
            > and covered in <Link
              href="https://www.businessweekly.co.uk/posts/chuckit-takes-first-prize-in-arm-ai-developer-challenge"
              external>Business Weekly</Link
            >. <Link href="/dev/amanat">amanat</Link> scans an NGO's cloud accounts
            for exposed beneficiary data and remediates it on-device, so case files
            and biometric records never leave the machine. The line goes back to my
            time at UNICEF, where I built geospatial routing for school site planning,
            and continues through <Link href="/dev/askstreets">AskStreets</Link> and
            a climate-aware emergency routing tool for <Link href="/dev/our-era"
              >Brownsville, Brooklyn</Link
            > that won Best Community Communication Tool at the LEAP Climate Hackathon
            at the American Museum of Natural History.
          </p>
          <p>
            These projects share a subject I have worked on since I was an
            undergraduate: who gets seen, who gets counted, and what systems do
            to people who cannot opt out. I first took it up in writing, in <Link
              href="/blog/being-brown-this-election"
              >essays on surveillance and race</Link
            > and a <Link href="/dev/carceral-contagion"
              >simulation of how incarceration spreads</Link
            > through a community. I take it up now in an <Link
              href="/dev/race-faces-fairness"
              >audit of racial bias in commercial face recognition</Link
            > and in tools that protect the data of vulnerable people. What changed
            over the years was the medium, from essay to software, and not the question.
          </p>
          <p>
            I'm also a poet and theatermaker. My poetry has appeared in <Link
              href="https://www.barzakhmag.net/spring-2026-poetry-blog/2026/3/19/adam-munawar-rahman"
              external>Barzakh Magazine</Link
            >, <Link href="https://heartonoursleeves.press" external
              ><em>Collide-oscope</em></Link
            > (Heart on Our Sleeves Press), and <Link
              href="https://www.fourtulips.com/archives/padma"
              external>Four Tulips</Link
            >, where I was a finalist in the Fantastic Mischief Writing Contest.
            I've produced 34 shows, directed Ayad Akhtar's <em>Disgraced</em> at Wesleyan,
            stage-managed <Link
              href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/03/theater/really-really-gorgeous-review.html"
              external>Really Really Gorgeous</Link
            > at <Link href="https://thetanknyc.org/" external>The Tank</Link>,
            worked as a sound, set, and <Link href="/design"
              >graphic designer</Link
            >, and wrote theater criticism for <Link
              href="https://wesleyanargus.com/2017/11/13/gruesome-murders-hip-hop-breaks-totalitarian-states-the-pillowman-premieres-at-the-cfa-theater/"
              external>The Wesleyan Argus</Link
            >. Writing, theater, and software have always been one kind of work
            for me, which is making something in response to what I notice.
          </p>
        </article>

        <aside class="about-rail">
          <div class="rail-stack">
            <span class="rail-stack-label">At a glance</span>
            <ul class="rail-chips">
              <li class="rail-chip">Go</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">Python</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">Rust/WASM</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">TypeScript</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">z/OS</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">Grafana k6</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">MCP</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">Ansible</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">Jenkins</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">load testing</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">observability</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">agentic AI</li>
              <li class="rail-chip">geospatial</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <dl class="about-facts">
            <div class="fact-row">
              <dt>Based</dt>
              <dd>NYC &middot; Eastern Time</dd>
            </div>
            <div class="fact-row">
              <dt>Now</dt>
              <dd>Test automation lead, IBM Z &middot; NYU Tandon</dd>
            </div>
            <div class="fact-row">
              <dt>Education</dt>
              <dd>Wesleyan &middot; Theater & CS &middot; 2020</dd>
            </div>
            <div class="fact-row">
              <dt>GitHub</dt>
              <dd>
                <Link href="https://github.com/msradam" external>msradam</Link>
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="fact-row">
              <dt>LinkedIn</dt>
              <dd>
                <Link href="https://linkedin.com/in/adamsrahman" external
                  >adamsrahman</Link
                >
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="fact-row">
              <dt>Medium</dt>
              <dd>
                <Link href="https://medium.com/@msradam" external>@msradam</Link
                >
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Container>
</Layout>

<style>
  .about-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 160px;
    gap: 3rem;
    align-items: start;
  }

  .about-rail {
    padding-top: 0.25rem;
  }

  .rail-stack {
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .rail-stack-label {
    display: block;
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: var(--label); /* VT323 optical bump from 0.611 */
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text-2);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .rail-chips {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.3rem;
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .rail-chip {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 0.667rem; /* VT323 optical bump from 0.583 */
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--text-2);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    padding: 0.08rem 0.4rem;
    background: var(--bg-alt);
  }

  .about-facts {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0;
  }

  .fact-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    padding: 0.6rem 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }

  .fact-row:first-child {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }

  .fact-row dt {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 0.667rem; /* VT323 optical bump from 0.611 */
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text-2);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .fact-row dd {
    font-family: var(--sans);
    font-size: 0.833rem;
    color: var(--text-2);
    margin: 0.15rem 0 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .about-layout {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 2rem;
    }

    .about-rail {
      order: -1;
    }
  }
</style>
